  "business_context": "Quote records hold the formal pricing proposals that get sent to customers for sign-off. They sit between Opportunity (the deal in pursuit) and Order (the executed purchase). One Opportunity often has multiple Quotes — a Bronze / Silver / Gold tier presentation, or a proposal-with-and-without-add-ons comparison, or revised pricing after negotiation. The \"primary\" or \"synced\" Quote is the one whose pricing drives the Opportunity's Amount. Quotes carry their own line items (Quote Line Items in Salesforce, separate from Opportunity Line Items), customer-facing identifiers (Quote Number), expiration dates (after which the quote is invalid), terms and conditions, and approval status. In subscription / SaaS sales motions, Quotes capture subscription term, start date, billing frequency, and ramp pricing — the Salesforce CPQ product extends standard Quotes significantly to handle these. In nonprofit deployments Quotes are rare; they appear when nonprofits sell products (event tickets, merchandise, services) but most fundraising motions don't use Quotes. When interviewing clients, surface \"Quote\" by asking whether they need to generate formal pricing documents to send to customers, whether multiple pricing variations are quoted per opportunity, and whether quotes need approval workflows. If yes to any of these, the target backend's Quote support matters; if no, this entity is not needed.",
